HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has published a 14% increase in the number of HIV and AIDS citizens.
More than 820,000 people in the country have been affected, says the health authorities.
In the second quarter of 2018, only 40,000 new cases were registered.
The vast majority of the new cases were sexually transmitted, which is a new trend.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly in some parts of China because of infected blood transfusions.
But the number of people receiving HIV in this way has been reduced to something near zero, says Chinese health authorities at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, in one year the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is an acute problem in China’s LGBT environment.
In 1997 homosexuality was legalised, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be a widespread phenomenon.
Studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with other men marry women sooner or later because of their conservative values.
Many cases of infection are due to a lack of prevention in these conditions.
Since 2003, the Chinese Government has promised free and equal access to HIV medicine as an attempt to solve the problem.
