What is the Global Citizens Festival and has it done something to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, New York hosts the Global Citizens Festival – an annual music festival with a very impressive selection of artists and an equally impressive goal; to end the world’s poverty.
For the seventh time, the Global Citizens Festival will receive tens of thousands of people on Central Park’s large lawn, where they can look forward to concerts with Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes. At the same time, the festival will attract attention to the real goal of ending extreme poverty in 2030.
Global Citizen Festival started in 2012 and is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international interest organisation that fights to end poverty by increasing the number of active opponents.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (if you don't want to pay for a VIP ticket), concert fans must perform a number of tasks or "actions". For example, do voluntary work, write to a world leader, make a phone call or any other meaningful action that can draw attention to the goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been now that they have 12 years left to reach the goal?
Does the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really change, or is it just another case of so-called "clickivism" – i.e. that people feel that they make a difference by signing a signature on the web or making a Twitter lookup?
Global Citizen reports that since 2011, they have registered more than 19 million "actions" from their members aimed at different goals.
They believe that these actions have encouraged world leaders to make binding objectives and political measures that are equivalent to more than $37 billion, which are expected to have affected more than 2.25 billion people in 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group listed 390 objectives and actions that had become due to their actions, which ran up to over 10 billion dollars, which had already been paid or collected.
The Group estimates that so far these funds have had a direct impact on almost 649 million people worldwide.
