The study is carried out by scientists from Scotland’s National Trust and follows common bats, dwarf bats, long-haired bats and water bats at the Inverewe Gardens in West Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed in carefully selected locations in the area to record the activities of the bats throughout the season.
Data from NTS personnel and volunteers are also collected using handheld detectors.
In-depth analysis of the sound recordings will reveal the frequencies of the bat calls and show what kind of action is taking.
To produce a detailed landscape view of their behavior, a report and a map of the habitat are made.
NTS Rob Dewar Nature Conservation Adviser hopes that the results reveal which areas of the habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help to determine the benefits of habitat conservation, such as the establishment of meadows, and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has fallen dramatically over the last 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban expansion projects that affect shipowners and restrict their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a danger. The same can include flu traps, chemical treatment of building materials and attacks from pets.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because they primarily hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use an advanced eco-localisation technique to find insects and fly around obstacles.
NTS, responsible for the conservation of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 acres of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts who often collect data, inspect shipowners and sometimes make rescue operations.
The organization has even made Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the area around Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten of Scotland's bats.
David Thompson, responsible for the area, says it is an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threeve we have a very good area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the good habitat.
There is much you don't know about bats, so work here and elsewhere can help to understand what they need to thrive."
He emphasises the importance of looking for bats before performing maintenance tasks on properties, as the destruction of a single nest can kill up to 400 females and cubs, thus risking the destruction of an entire local population.
The bat is protected, and it is illegal to kill, bother or disturb them or their shipowners.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish project manager for Bat Conservation Trust, has called on the public to give a hand.
