Update on algae flowering: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decreasing alga concentration in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, scattered flowering is reported in the area around Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – suggesting that the concentration is decreasing.
The flowering of algae spreads over a coastline of 210 km from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
There are less flowers about 16 km from the coast in Hillsborough County, but there are fewer than last week.
Flowers have also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported at or at sea in Pinellas County during the last week, low to high concentrations in the sea off in Hillsborough County, background concentration at high concentrations in Manatee County, background concentration at high concentrations in or at sea off Sarasota County, background concentration at medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background concentration at high concentrations in or at sea off Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are continued reports of respiratory distress in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory distress has been reported in northwest Florida in the past week.
